comments.body:
Hi [~spark],

Following is the problem seen with Eucalyptus DNS server today:

*Failure Case*

a) Download and install a CentOS 6.5 EMI. For this example I took our ELB image because currently only HVM image would work in 4.0.0 and I could not find a CentOS 6.5 HVM EMI on our website emis.eucalyptus.com. Anyways once the ELB instance is up , I logged into it.

b) Resolver

{code}
search eucalyptus.internal
nameserver 10.104.1.211
{code}

Note that it points to the CLC IP. Hence we completely rely on the CLC DNS server to resolve DNS names.

c) From the ELB instance try to ssh to a server on internet

{code}
[root@euca-10-105-3-9 ~]# ssh jeevanullas.in
ssh: Could not resolve hostname jeevanullas.in: Name or service not known
{code}

Immediately fails returning an error that DNS could not resolve name. Ok. Lets try to find out more.

d) Perform A record lookup for jeevanullas.in via CLC DNS server

{code}
[root@euca-10-105-3-9 ~]# dig jeevanullas.in

; <<>> DiG 9.8.2rc1-RedHat-9.8.2-0.23.rc1.el6_5.1 <<>> jeevanullas.in
;; global options: +cmd
;; Got answer:
;; ->>HEADER<<- opcode: QUERY, status: NOERROR, id: 5074
;; flags: qr rd ra; QUERY: 1, ANSWER: 1, AUTHORITY: 3, ADDITIONAL: 3

;; QUESTION SECTION:
;jeevanullas.in.			IN	A

;; ANSWER SECTION:
jeevanullas.in.		2760	IN	A	188.40.110.37

;; AUTHORITY SECTION:
jeevanullas.in.		2760	IN	NS	a.dns.gandi.net.
jeevanullas.in.		2760	IN	NS	c.dns.gandi.net.
jeevanullas.in.		2760	IN	NS	b.dns.gandi.net.

;; ADDITIONAL SECTION:
a.dns.gandi.net.	31317	IN	A	173.246.97.2
c.dns.gandi.net.	27507	IN	A	217.70.182.20
b.dns.gandi.net.	42120	IN	A	217.70.184.40

;; Query time: 10 msec
;; SERVER: 10.104.1.211#53(10.104.1.211)
;; WHEN: Tue Apr 22 09:40:09 2014
;; MSG SIZE  rcvd: 157
{code}

Wow. this works just fine. Then what was the problem with SSH?

e) Found out that ssh command will work if the option "-4" is passed to the command like this:

{code}
[root@euca-10-105-3-9 ~]# ssh -4 jeevanullas.in
The authenticity of host 'jeevanullas.in (188.40.110.37)' can't be established.
RSA key fingerprint is 93:3e:b6:30:fd:f0:3f:d2:fe:05:4e:a4:f6:30:b9:02.
Are you sure you want to continue connecting (yes/no)? yes
Warning: Permanently added 'jeevanullas.in,188.40.110.37' (RSA) to the list of known hosts.
reverse mapping checking getaddrinfo for jeevanullas.vps.miniorb.in [188.40.110.37] failed - POSSIBLE BREAK-IN ATTEMPT!
root@jeevanullas.in's password: 
Last login: Tue Jan 28 14:15:06 2014 from 114.143.34.51
[root@jeevanullas ~]# 
{code}

The "-4" option passed via SSH forces the query type to "A" instead of the default precedence that is try out "AAAA" if no record present then try "A".

f) Now edit /etc/resolv.conf and configure google DNS server IP , comment eucalyptus CLC DNS server IP. Hence the file looks like this:

{code}
[root@euca-10-105-3-9 ~]# cat /etc/resolv.conf
; generated by /sbin/dhclient-script
search eucalyptus.internal
# nameserver 10.104.1.211
nameserver 8.8.4.4
{code}

g) Now retry SSH command to host on internet without passing any option (this time it will follow the precedence order):

{code}
[root@euca-10-105-3-9 ~]# ssh jeevanullas.in
reverse mapping checking getaddrinfo for jeevanullas.vps.miniorb.in [188.40.110.37] failed - POSSIBLE BREAK-IN ATTEMPT!
root@jeevanullas.in's password:
{code}

As can be seen it works. Debugging this further, following was found via "host" command (part of bind-utils) inside the instance

h) When the DNS server used is google DNS server then following is seen

{code}
[root@euca-10-105-3-9 ~]# host -t AAAA jeevanullas.in
jeevanullas.in has no AAAA record
{code}

Note here the query type used specifically is AAAA and answer is "no AAAA record"

i) When the DNS server used is Eucalyptus CLC DNS server then following is seen

{code}
[root@euca-10-105-3-9 ~]# host -t AAAA jeevanullas.in
;; Warning: query response not set
jeevanullas.in.eucalyptus.internal has no AAAA record
{code}

As can be seen when it went to eucalyptus CLC DNS server the "search" string from resolv.conf got appended to the DNS name "jeevanullas.in" i.e "eucalyptus.internal" nothing like this happened when querying against Google DNS server. Perhaps this behaviour needs a separate EUCA ticket.

Now after removing the search string "eucalyptus.internal" from resolv.conf we retry again:

{code}
[root@euca-10-105-3-9 ~]# host -t AAAA jeevanullas.in
;; Warning: query response not set
;; Warning: query response not set
Host jeevanullas.in not found: 2(SERVFAIL)
{code}

The above is response from Eucalyptus CLC DNS server. As can be seen this has failed with SERVFAIL compared to the result from Google DNS server that said no AAAA record was found for host jeevanullas.in

This is the problem that needs to be fixed in Eucalyptus CLC DNS server IMHO so that client like ssh does not have to force the query type to "A" in order to get correct result.

Now looking at the code specifically in ConnectionHandler.java:

{code}
      sr = DnsResolvers.findRecords(response, response.getQuestion( ), ConnectionHandler.getRemoteInetAddress( ) );
      if ( sr != null ) {
        if ( sr.isSuccessful( ) ) {
          return Rcode.NOERROR;
        } else if ( sr.isNXDOMAIN( ) ) {
          return Rcode.NXDOMAIN;
        }
      }
    } catch ( Exception ex ) {
      Logger.getLogger( DnsResolvers.class ).error( ex );
    }
		Zone zone = findBestZone(name);
		if (zone != null) {
			if (type == Type.AAAA) {
				addSOA(response, zone);
				response.getHeader().setFlag(Flags.AA);
				return (Rcode.NOERROR);
			}
			sr = zone.findRecords(name, type);
		}
		else {
			Cache cache = getCache(dclass);
			sr = cache.lookupRecords(name, type, Credibility.NORMAL);
		}

		if (sr.isUnknown()) {
      return (Rcode.SERVFAIL);
		}
{code}

In case of failure response object "sr" is "Unknown" causing the return code to be sent as SERVFAIL as seen below

{code}
[root@euca-10-105-3-9 ~]# dig AAAA jeevanullas.in @8.8.4.4

; <<>> DiG 9.8.2rc1-RedHat-9.8.2-0.23.rc1.el6_5.1 <<>> AAAA jeevanullas.in @8.8.4.4
;; global options: +cmd
;; Got answer:
;; ->>HEADER<<- opcode: QUERY, status: NOERROR, id: 33167
;; flags: qr rd ra; QUERY: 1, ANSWER: 0, AUTHORITY: 1, ADDITIONAL: 0

;; QUESTION SECTION:
;jeevanullas.in.			IN	AAAA

;; AUTHORITY SECTION:
jeevanullas.in.		1799	IN	SOA	a.dns.gandi.net. hostmaster.gandi.net. 1327658586 10800 3600 604800 10800

;; Query time: 125 msec
;; SERVER: 8.8.4.4#53(8.8.4.4)
;; WHEN: Tue Apr 22 11:00:47 2014
;; MSG SIZE  rcvd: 94

[root@euca-10-105-3-9 ~]# dig AAAA jeevanullas.in @10.104.1.211
;; Warning: query response not set

; <<>> DiG 9.8.2rc1-RedHat-9.8.2-0.23.rc1.el6_5.1 <<>> AAAA jeevanullas.in @10.104.1.211
;; global options: +cmd
;; Got answer:
;; ->>HEADER<<- opcode: QUERY, status: SERVFAIL, id: 49513
;; flags: rd; QUERY: 1, ANSWER: 0, AUTHORITY: 0, ADDITIONAL: 0
;; WARNING: recursion requested but not available

;; QUESTION SECTION:
;jeevanullas.in.			IN	AAAA

;; Query time: 2 msec
;; SERVER: 10.104.1.211#53(10.104.1.211)
;; WHEN: Tue Apr 22 11:00:51 2014
;; MSG SIZE  rcvd: 32
{code}

Now taking a more deep dive into the current Eucalyptus CLC DNS server code , we go in RecursiveDnsResolver.java , specifically this code section in lookupRecords method

{code}
    Record[] found = aLookup.run( );
    List<Record> queriedrrs = Arrays.asList( found != null
      ? found : new Record[] {} );
{code}

In case of query type AAAA the aLookup.run() resulted in NULL hence found was set to NULL. Now moving in the same method there are basically 3 for loops for different type of queries

{code}
 for ( Name cnameRec : cnames ) {
      SetResponse sr = cache.lookupRecords( cnameRec, Type.CNAME, Credibility.ANY );
      if ( sr != null && sr.isSuccessful( ) && sr.answers( ) != null ) {
        for ( RRset result : sr.answers( ) ) {
          Iterator rrs = result.rrs( false );
          if ( rrs != null ) {
            for ( Object record : ImmutableSet.copyOf( rrs ) ) {
              answer.add( ( Record ) record );
            }
          }
        }
      }
    }
    for ( Record queriedRec : queriedrrs ) {
      SetResponse sr = cache.lookupRecords( queriedRec.getName( ),
        queriedRec.getType( ),
        Credibility.ANY );
      if ( sr != null && sr.isSuccessful( ) && sr.answers( ) != null ) {
        for ( RRset result : sr.answers( ) ) {
          Iterator rrs = result.rrs( false );
          if ( rrs != null ) {
            for ( Object record : ImmutableSet.copyOf( rrs ) ) {
              answer.add( ( Record ) record );
            }
          }
        }
      }
    }
    for ( Record aRec : queriedrrs ) {
      List<Record> nsRecs = lookupNSRecords( aRec.getName( ), cache );
      for ( Record nsRec : nsRecs ) {
        authority.add( nsRec );
        Lookup nsLookup = new Lookup( ( ( NSRecord ) nsRec ).getTarget( ), type );
        nsLookup.setCache( cache );
        Record[] nsAnswers = nsLookup.run( );
        if ( nsAnswers != null ) {
          additional.addAll( Arrays.asList( nsAnswers ) );
        }
      }
    }
{code}

The code here is not commented so this is just my assumption, the first for loop if for CNAME record types, the 2nd for loop is for already cached records and finally the 3rd if for record type A.

None of these 3 for loops is executed in case of AAAA query type causing it to return "answer" as 0 which is fine but still we should have send "authority" as "1" because the google DNS server returns 1 authority. I think we need a code block in between these 3 for loops that handle the AAAA record type and the function of that code block should be to set the "authority" section and set the response type to NOERROR instead of UNKNOWN causing a SERVFAIL eventually.

Please let me know if you have any questions.

Cheers!
Deependra
